Ensure that you are using the ViewHolder pattern in your getView method. This pattern is used to recycle views efficiently. If you are not using it, consider modifying your getView method like this:

    override fun getView(position: Int, convertView: View?, parent: ViewGroup): View {
        val binding: ItemMultiSpinnerGetviewBinding
        if (convertView == null) {
            val inflater = LayoutInflater.from(context)
            binding = ItemMultiSpinnerGetviewBinding.inflate(inflater, parent, false)
            binding.root.tag = binding
        } else {
            binding = convertView.tag as ItemMultiSpinnerGetviewBinding
        }
    
        binding.tvBeforeClickedMultiSpinner.text = dataList[position].text
    
        return binding.root
    }

*Avoid calling notifyDataSetChanged() inside getView. It&#39;s generally not recommended and can lead to unexpected behavior. Instead, use it outside the getView method when you want to notify the adapter that the underlying data has changed.*

**In your case, remove the notifyDataSetChanged() call from within the getView method.**

In Android, the getView method in the adapter is designed to be called multiple times, especially in scenarios where views are being recycled for efficiency, such as when scrolling or selecting items in a Spinner. However, calling notifyDataSetChanged() within the getDropDownView method is problematic and can lead to undesired behavior.

**Remove notifyDataSetChanged() from getDropDownView:**

    override fun getDropDownView(position: Int, convertView: View?, parent: ViewGroup): View {
        val binding: ItemMultiSpinnerGetviewBinding = if (convertView == null) {
            ItemMultiSpinnerGetviewBinding.inflate(LayoutInflater.from(context), parent, false)
                .also {
                    it.root.tag = it
                }
        } else {
            convertView.tag as ItemMultiSpinnerGetviewBinding
        }
    
        binding.tvBeforeClickedMultiSpinner.text = dataList[position].text
    
        return binding.root
    }

Move the logic inside checkedListener outside of getDropDownView. You should not trigger data changes or adapter notifications within the getDropDownView method.

    // Call this method when you want to update the data and notify the adapter
    fun updateData() {
        checkedListener(dataList, position)
        notifyDataSetChanged()
    }
    
    // Modify your getDropDownView method accordingly
    override fun getDropDownView(position: Int, convertView: View?, parent: ViewGroup): View {
        // ...
        return binding.root
    }

Make sure that updateData() is called at the appropriate time and not excessively. You should call it when the underlying data has changed, and you want to reflect those changes in the UI.

*By making these changes, you should be able to address the issue of getView being called multiple times and avoid the potential side effects of calling notifyDataSetChanged() within getDropDownView.*

